  "What does FDIC insurance protect?": "",
  "Investment losses in the stock market": "",
  "Bank deposits up to $250,000 per depositor, per institution, in case the bank fails": "",
  "Cryptocurrency held in digital wallets": "",
  "Identity theft and fraud on all accounts": "",
  "The Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation insures bank deposits up to $250,000 per depositor, per insured institution. If a bank fails, depositors are guaranteed to recover their insured funds, making savings accounts extremely safe.": "",
  "What is the 'pay yourself first' approach to emergency fund building?": "",
  "Paying your emergency fund contribution only after all bills and wants are paid": "",
  "Paying yourself a bonus when savings goals are met": "",
  "Using emergency fund money for personal purchases before bills": "",
  "Automatically transferring money to your emergency fund before paying discretionary expenses": "",
  "Pay yourself first means treating emergency fund contributions as a top-priority, non-negotiable expense. By automating the transfer before discretionary spending occurs, the fund grows consistently.": "",
  "What is a certificate of deposit (CD)?": "",
  "A document certifying stock ownership": "",
  "A type of checking account with no fees": "",
  "A time-deposit account that pays a fixed interest rate for a set period, with penalties for early withdrawal": "",
  "A government bond for education savings": "",
  "A CD locks your money for a specified term (3 months to 5 years) in exchange for a guaranteed, often higher, interest rate. Early withdrawal typically incurs a penalty, making CDs better for savings goals with known timelines.": "",
  "What does 'liquidity' mean in personal finance?": "",
  "How quickly and easily an asset can be converted to cash without significant loss of value": "",
  "The amount of cash in your wallet, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "How much debt you have within the broader context of highly analysis": "",
  "Your monthly income level when considering all relevant highly factors": "",
  "Liquidity measures how readily an asset converts to spendable cash. A savings account is highly liquid (instant access), while real estate is illiquid (selling takes weeks or months). Emergency funds must be highly liquid.": "",
  "What is a CD ladder?": "",
  "A strategy of spreading savings across CDs with staggered maturity dates to balance higher rates with periodic access": "",
  "A CD that automatically renews at maturity": "",
  "A list ranking CDs from highest to lowest interest rate": "",
  "A physical ladder used in bank vaults": "",
  "A CD ladder divides savings into multiple CDs with different maturity dates (e.g., 3-month, 6-month, 12-month). As each CD matures, you either use the money or reinvest, giving you regular access while earning higher rates.": "",
  "What is the difference between a savings goal and an emergency fund?": "",
  "A savings goal is for a planned future purchase; an emergency fund is for unexpected, unplanned expenses": "",
  "An emergency fund earns more interest than a savings goal": "",
  "There is no difference; they serve the same purpose": "",
  "Savings goals require more money than emergency funds": "",
  "Savings goals target known future expenses (vacation, car, home down payment) with specific amounts and timelines. Emergency funds protect against unknown, unexpected events (job loss, medical bills, urgent repairs) without a planned use date.": "",
  "What does 'mental accounting' mean in the context of savings?": "",
  "Calculating savings in your head without a calculator": "",
  "An accounting method used only by businesses": "",
  "Memorizing your account balances": "",
  "Assigning different purposes to money in separate mental or physical categories to improve discipline and motivation": "",
  "Mental accounting involves labeling money for specific purposes. Having separate savings accounts named 'Emergency Fund,' 'Vacation,' and 'Car Fund' makes you less likely to raid one fund for another purpose because each has a clear identity.": "",
  "What is APY (Annual Percentage Yield)?": "",
  "The annual limit on savings account deposits": "",
  "The effective annual rate of return on a savings account, including the effect of compound interest": "",
  "The annual penalty for early CD withdrawal": "",
  "The annual fee charged by a bank": "",
  "APY reflects the true annual return on savings, accounting for how often interest is compounded. A 4.5% APY with daily compounding means you earn slightly more than a simple 4.5% annual rate because interest earns interest throughout the year.": "",
  "Taylor has $2,800/month in essential expenses and currently has $5,000 in emergency savings. She wants a 6-month fund. How much more does she need, and if she saves $400/month, how many months until she reaches her goal?": "",
